A computer system is made up of hardware and software components that work together to process, store, and transmit data.

Main Hardware Components:

CPU (Central Processing Unit)
The CPU is the “brain” of the computer. It executes instructions and performs calculations.

Key functions:
Processes instructions from software
Performs arithmetic and logic operations
Controls other hardware components


RAM (Random Access Memory)
RAM is temporary memory used while a computer is running.

Key characteristics:
Fast access speed
Data is lost when the computer is turned off
Stores active processes and applications


Storage (HDD / SSD)
Storage holds data permanently.

Types:
HDD (Hard Disk Drive): slower, mechanical
SSD (Solid State Drive): faster, no moving parts

Used for:
Operating systems
Applications
User files


Motherboard
The motherboard connects all hardware components together and allows communication between them.

It includes:
CPU socket
RAM slots
Storage connections
Peripheral ports


Power Supply Unit (PSU)

The PSU provides power to all components inside the computer.
It converts electricity from an outlet into usable power for the system.


Software in a Computer System
Software provides instructions for hardware to execute.

System Software
Operating systems (Windows, Linux, macOS)
Manages hardware resources

Application Software
Web browsers
Games
Productivity tools


Data Processing Cycle
A computer processes data in a cycle:

Input (data is received)
Processing (CPU processes data)
Output (results are shown)
Storage (data is saved if needed)


How Components Work Together

Example: opening a program

Stored program is loaded from SSD into RAM
CPU retrieves instructions from RAM
CPU processes instructions
Output is displayed on screen


Why It Matters in Cybersecurity

Understanding computer internals helps:

Identify malware behavior (CPU/RAM usage)
Analyze system performance issues
Understand how exploits affect memory
Investigate system compromise

Key Takeaways:
A computer system combines hardware and software.
CPU processes instructions, RAM stores active data, and storage keeps permanent files.
The motherboard connects all components.
The OS manages communication between hardware and software.
Understanding system internals is essential for cybersecurity analysis.
